{"add":{"doc":{"id":"309e0afd6008a9c42783050458358924141b968e020c1ab3e430d7544a690dd9","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Tauyuan_SARS_Checkpoint_1.jpg/220px-Tauyuan_SARS_Checkpoint_1.jpg","previous":["Global health is the health of populations in a global context that transcends the perspectives and concerns of individual nations.[195] Health problems that transcend national borders or have a global political and economic impact are emphasized.[196] It has been defined as 'the area of study, research and practice that places a priority on improving health and achieving equity in health for all people worldwide'.[197] Thus, global health is about worldwide improvement of health, reduction of disparities, and protection against global threats that disregard national borders.[198] The application of these principles to the domain of mental health is called Global Mental Health.[199]"],"after":["The major international agency for health is the World Health Organization (WHO). Other important agencies with impact on global health activities include UNICEF, World Food Programme (WFP), United Nations University International Institute for Global Health and the World Bank. A major initiative for improved global health is the United Nations Millennium Declaration and the globally endorsed Millennium Development Goals.[200]"]}}}